# Description
This folder contains some examples on how to integrate CAMEL with Snakemake.


# Notes
- In order to run the scripts, the home of the Camel instance needs to be added to the PYTHONPATH:
export PYTHONPATH='PATH_TO_CAMEL'

- You can change the config file to change the location of the input files and the directories.

- If you want to have clean working directories for each tool you can surround Camel IO entries in the output
specification with temp(*). This will ensure that they are deleted when they are not needed anymore. Leaving you with a
working directory as you would have on the command line.


# Example 1: Read trimming as separate tools
The 'read_trimming-tools.snakefile' shows how to use the SnakemakeUtils module.
You can run it by using the following command:

snakemake --cores 16 --snakefile read_trimming-tools.snakefile --configfile config.yaml


# Example 2: Read trimming as a pipeline
The 'read_trimming-pipeline' shows how to run the same pipeline as a SnakePipeline. A pipeline has the additional
functionality of loading parameters from database and logging parameters, input and output files.

Running as a pipeline requires an additional main script that generates a config file on the fly. It can be executed as
follows:

python run_read_trimming_pipeline.py

The database logging is disabled by default (to avoid cluttering the database). It can be enabled by setting the global
variable DB_LOGGING to True. You can verify afterwards that the initial input, parameters and output files are logged
in the database.
